/wiki/Daegu_Korea_Powertrain_FC: Daegu KAPEC FC (Korean: 대구 한국파워트레인 축구단) is a South Korean association football club based in the city of Daegu. It was a member of the K3 League in 2007, but withdrew from the league when unable to find a suitable home venue for the 2008 season.
/wiki/Changwon_United_FC: Changwon United FC was a South Korean football club, based in Changwon. Founded as Changwon Doodae FC in 1998, the club changed its name to Changwon United FC in August 2007. It used to be a member of the K3 League, but withdrew from it during the 2008 season.
/wiki/Seoul_Pabal_FC: Seoul Pabal FC was a South Korean soccer club based in Eunpyeong-gu, Seoul. It was a member of the K3 League, an amateur league and the third tier of league football in South Korea.
/wiki/Jeonju_Ongoeul_FC: Jeonju Ongoeul was a South Korean soccer club based in the city of Jeonju. It was a member of the K3 League, an amateur league and the third tier of league football in South Korea.
/wiki/Samcheok_Shinwoo_Electronics_FC: Samcheok Shinwoo Electronics FC was a South Korean football club based in the city of Samcheok.  It was established in Hwaseong in 2006 as Hwaseong Shinwoo Electronics FC.  It moved its home to Samcheok in 2008, changing its name to Samcheok Shinwoo Electronics FC.  It was a member of the Challengers League, an amateur league and the fourth tier of league football in South Korea. The club withdraw from the league at the end of the 2010 season.
/wiki/Yongin_Citizen_FC: Yongin Citizen Football Club was a South Korean football club based in the city of Yongin. It was a member of the K3 League, an amateur league and the fourth tier of league football in South Korea, but withdrew from the league in 2010 due to financial difficulties.
/wiki/Bucheon_FC_1995: Bucheon FC 1995 is a South Korean professional football club located in the city of Bucheon, which is currently a member of the K League 2. The club was founded by a group of former Bucheon SK supporters after the move of Bucheon SK to Jeju at the beginning of 2006.
/wiki/K_League_2: The K League 2 (Hangul: K리그2) is a South Korean professional association football league. Being the second tier of the South Korean football league system, it is currently contested by ten clubs, and operates on a system of promotion and relegation with the K League 1.
/wiki/Namyangju_United_FC: Namyangju United Football Club is a South Korean soccer club based in the city of Namyangju. It is a member of the Challengers League, an amateur league and the fourth tier of league football in South Korea.
/wiki/Asan_United_FC: Asan United was a South Korean football club based in the city of Asan. It was a founder member of the Challengers League, an amateur league and the third tier of league football in South Korea in 2007. The club was dissolved in 2015 after merging with Cheonan FC.
/wiki/Seoul_FC_Martyrs: Seoul FC Martyrs was a South Korean football club based in the Gangbuk-gu district of Seoul.
/wiki/Yeonggwang_FC: Jeonnam Yeonggwang Football Club (Korean: 전남 영광 FC), also known as Chunnam Youngkwang FC, is a South Korean football club based in Yeonggwang, South Jeolla. From 2010 season, Jeonnam Yeonggwang FC plays in the Challengers League, the third tier of Korean football. Yeonggwang FC's home stadium is Yeonggwang Sportium.
/wiki/Busan_FC: Busan FC is a South Korean football club based in the Busan. The club is a member of the K3 League Basic, an semi-professional league football in South Korea, since the 2017 season.
/wiki/Buyeo_FC: Buyeo FC is a South Korean football club based in the county of Buyeo. The club is a member of the K3 League, an semi-professional league and the fourth tier of league football in South Korea, since the 2016 season.
/wiki/Cheongju_City_FC: Cheongju City Football Club was a South Korean football club based in the city of Cheongju. The club, originally named Cheonan FC and based in the city of Cheonan, rebranded to Cheongju City FC in February 2016. In October 2018, the club merged with Cheongju FC.
/wiki/Cheongju_FC: Cheongju FC is a South Korean football club based in the city of Cheongju, currently playing in the K3 League, the third division of South Korean football.
/wiki/FC_Uijeongbu:
FC Uijeongbu (Korean: FC 의정부) is a South Korean amateur football club based in Uijeongbu, South Korea. They currently play in the K3 League Basic, fifth
tier of the South Korean football league system.
/wiki/Chungju_Citizen_FC: Chungju Citizen FC is a South Korean football club based in the city of Chungju. The club is a member of the K4 League, a semi-professional league and the fourth tier of football in South Korea, since the 2020 season.
/wiki/K4_League: The K4 League is a semi-professional football competition in South Korea. Created in 2020, it is a considered the fourth tier of South Korean football league system. After the 2019 season, the former K3 League Basic went defunct and got rebranded into the K4 League.
/wiki/Seoul_Nowon_United_FC: Seoul Nowon United FC (Korean: 서울 노원 유나이티드 FC) is a South Korean semi-professional football club based in Nowon District, Seoul. It currently competes in the fourth tier of the South Korean football league system, the K4 League. Until 2018, the club was named Seoul United FC.
/wiki/Seoul_Jungnang_FC: Seoul Jungnang FC (Hangul: 서울 중랑 축구단) is a South Korean football club based in the city of Jungnang-gu, Seoul.
/wiki/Pocheon_Citizen_FC: Pocheon Citizen FC is a South Korean football club based in the city of Pocheon. The club is a member of the K4 League, a semi-professional league and the fourth tier of league football in South Korea.
/wiki/Icheon_Citizen_FC: Icheon Citizen FC (Korean: 이천 시민축구단) is a South Korean football club based in Icheon City. It is a member of the K4 League, a semi-professional league and the fourth tier of football in South Korea. The club was founded in 2009.
